  "name": "Access and Indemnity Agreement (Due Diligence)",
  "summary": "This skill produces a production-ready US commercial real estate Access and Indemnity Agreement governing prospective buyer access during due diligence, with operational access controls, a clear non-invasive versus invasive testing framework, insurance and endorsement requirements matched to claims reality, indemnity and defense provisions addressing the critical 'discovery' carve-out for pre-existing conditions, restoration and lien remediation remedies, and confidentiality and report-handling terms with strategic guidance on the 'actual knowledge' trap. It embeds adversarial and insurer-facing drafting judgment, addresses state-specific anti-indemnity statutes, and includes explicit anti-hallucination guardrails requiring web verification or [VERIFY] flags for jurisdiction-dependent legal standards. All outputs require attorney review.",
  "content": "# Access and Indemnity Agreement (Due Diligence) \u2014 US Commercial Real Estate\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill guides the practitioner through drafting an execution-ready Property Access and Indemnity Agreement (sometimes called a \"Right of Entry\" or \"Access Letter\") for use in commercial real estate transactions. The work product is a short-form but high-stakes risk-allocation contract: it gives a prospective buyer and its consultants permission to enter a property to perform inspections, while shifting operational and third-party liability risk away from the owner during a period when the owner is not yet receiving purchase consideration and has limited control over who is on site.\n\nWhen done poorly, these agreements create predictable failure modes: unpermitted invasive testing that triggers environmental or structural damage; uninsured contractors entering the site; tenant disruption leading to lease claims; ambiguous indemnity that fails to cover the owner's actual exposure; and confidentiality gaps that allow sensitive tenant or financial information to circulate. A professionally competent access agreement reads like a disciplined operating protocol\u2014who can enter, when, to do what, under what safety and insurance regime, with what restoration obligations\u2014and it anticipates scrutiny from property managers, tenants, insurers, and, if something goes wrong, litigators and claims adjusters.\n\nWhile often viewed as a \"standard\" or \"preliminary\" form, improperly drafted access agreements can expose a property owner to catastrophic mechanics' liens, environmental liability, or uninsured personal injury claims. Conversely, an overly restrictive agreement can prevent a buyer from uncovering latent defects, leading to post-closing litigation or rescission claims. A successful execution of this skill results in a document that balances the buyer's need for thorough investigation with the owner's need for zero interference and total protection.\n\nScope boundary: this skill is for drafting the access agreement itself. It does not draft the Purchase and Sale Agreement (\"PSA\"), a full nondisclosure agreement (though it may include a confidentiality clause or cross-reference one), or jurisdiction-specific statutory rider language (e.g., special environmental disclosure regimes) without user-provided jurisdiction details and attorney verification.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nAn access and indemnity agreement exists because diligence often starts before, or runs parallel to, a definitive PSA. Even when a PSA exists, owners frequently want a standalone document that can be handed to consultants, property management, and security as a clear set of ground rules. The PSA itself typically lacks the granular operational detail required for pre-closing site visits.\n\nStrategically, this document serves three primary constituencies. First, the owner's risk manager, who demands that no one enters the property without adequate insurance and a contractual promise to pay for damages. Second, the buyer's environmental and engineering consultants, who need to know exactly what kind of testing is permitted and what approvals are required for invasive work such as soil borings. Third, the owner's legal counsel, who wants to ensure that the buyer's discovery of contamination or defects does not immediately become the owner's liability through forced disclosure or an argument that the owner now has \"actual knowledge.\"\n\nFrom a litigation perspective, this document is the primary defense against claims arising from consultant injuries, damage to building infrastructure during a Phase II environmental study, or tenant complaints about disruption. It also prevents the creation of an unintentional easement or leasehold interest by explicitly characterizing the entry as a revocable license. Sellers also use the agreement to constrain the scope and sequencing of diligence, manage tenant relationships and quiet enjoyment obligations, preserve privilege and confidentiality around sensitive reports, and prevent the buyer from creating a \"known condition\" record that later becomes a disclosure or remediation dispute.\n\nBuyers, in turn, need enough operational flexibility to complete diligence within the PSA's contingency period and to satisfy lender and equity requirements covering engineering, environmental, zoning, ADA, and life-safety assessments. The primary readers of this document are not just deal lawyers; property managers, onsite engineers, leasing teams, and third-party consultants will rely on it as an instruction set. If an incident occurs, insurers and litigators will treat it as the controlling allocation of risk, particularly for defense and additional insured tenders.\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore drafting, the LLM must obtain enough deal, property, and operational context to allocate risk in a way that is enforceable and commercially realistic. The LLM should request, review, and summarize the following inputs, and should pause to ask the user for any missing required information. Proceeding without these inputs often results in multiple revisions that delay the due diligence clock.\n\nFirst, collect the transaction context: whether there is a signed PSA or Letter of Intent; the diligence period dates and any extension rights; whether the buyer is under exclusivity; and whether the parties want the access agreement to terminate automatically if no PSA is executed. If a PSA exists, obtain the diligence and access clause so the access agreement can be consistent with it or expressly override it where intended.\n\nSecond, collect property and site context: property type (office, multifamily, industrial, retail, hotel, data center), address and any legal description exhibit, tenant occupancy status (fully leased versus vacant), union labor rules or site safety requirements, and whether there are special hazards such as roof access, confined spaces, high-voltage rooms, security-sensitive areas, controlled substances, or laboratories. Ask whether drones, thermal imaging, destructive probes, core samples, soil borings, groundwater wells, or geotechnical work is contemplated. Identify any specific areas that are off-limits, such as high-security server rooms or sensitive tenant spaces.\n\nThird, collect stakeholder information: full legal names and entity types for owner and buyer, plus property manager name; whether the buyer will use affiliates, lenders, and multiple consultants; and whether the owner requires all onsite persons to be licensed, insured, and pre-approved. If the Recipient is a newly formed special-purpose LLC, the owner should consider requiring a joinder or guaranty from a parent entity with actual assets to back the indemnity obligations. The LLM must flag the creditworthiness of the indemnitor as a primary concern if this situation is identified.\n\nFourth, collect insurance and risk parameters: owner's minimum limits and any insurer-driven or lender-driven requirements; whether the owner needs additional insured status on a primary and noncontributory basis; waiver of subrogation requirements; acceptable carrier quality standards (such as A-/VII AM Best rating or equivalent); and whether professional liability (errors and omissions) or Contractor's Pollution Liability (CPL) coverage is needed for environmental consultants or engineers performing invasive work. Ask if the owner wants a separate indemnity from each consultant or will accept the buyer's upstream indemnity.\n\nFifth, collect operational protocols: hours of access, notice lead time, escort requirements, sign-in and safety briefing procedures, personal protective equipment requirements, restrictions on tenant contact, photography rules, and requirements to use owner-approved vendors for certain building systems such as fire alarm or elevator testing.\n\nSixth, collect confidentiality and data handling expectations: whether an NDA exists; whether confidentiality must cover the existence of the negotiations; whether reports must be delivered to owner (noting the strategic implications discussed below); and whether owner requires a right to review or redact tenant-identifying information.\n\nFinally, collect the governing law, dispute forum, and whether the owner requires express equitable relief provisions for unauthorized entry or confidentiality breaches.\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Drafting Process\n\n### Step 1: Define the Deal Posture, Parties, Property, and the Legal Nature of the Right Being Granted\n\nThe drafting must begin by fixing the legal frame of the agreement: the right of entry is a temporary, revocable, non-exclusive license, not a lease, easement, or other real property interest. This distinction is vital. If the Recipient's presence were deemed a lease, the Owner might be forced into a lengthy eviction proceeding rather than a simple trespass action to remove a recalcitrant buyer. The Owner would also face unintended premises liability exposure under landlord-tenant doctrines. Your drafting should repeatedly reinforce that the buyer has no right of possession, no exclusive use, and must comply with the owner's reasonable rules.\n\nDraft the parties with full legal precision: legal name, entity type, state of organization, and principal address. Include the property manager if they will administer access; depending on local practice and risk tolerance, the manager may be an express third-party beneficiary of indemnity and insurance obligations.\n\nInclude recitals that do real work. Recitals should identify the owner's ownership interest in the property, describe the buyer's evaluation of a possible acquisition, and state that access is granted solely under the agreement's risk allocation framework. Avoid recitals that unintentionally promise a sale or create detrimental reliance.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how the grant of access should be framed:\n\n\"Owner grants Recipient a limited, revocable, non-exclusive license (and not a lease or other interest in real property) to enter the Property solely to perform the Investigations (as defined below) during the Access Period, subject to the rights of existing tenants, Owner's reasonable rules, and the terms of this Agreement. This Agreement creates a mere license and Recipient acknowledges that it shall not have any possession of or any interest in the Property.\"\n\nCommon mistakes at this stage include failing to define the \"Property\" precisely (especially when there are multiple parcels, shared parking, rooftop rights, or outparcels), failing to include the property manager and security team in the operational chain, and omitting a clear \"no agency\" or \"no authority\" clause. The latter can be important when buyers' contractors interact with tenants or vendors and might create apparent authority issues.\n\nFrom an adversarial perspective, if a claim arises, opposing counsel will look for ambiguity in who is covered as an \"Owner Indemnitee,\" whether the property manager is included, and whether the buyer's \"Representatives\" are defined broadly enough. Draft these definitions carefully and use them consistently throughout.\n\n### Step 2: Build an Operational Access Protocol That Is Enforceable on the Ground\n\nAn access agreement is as much an operating manual as a risk-shifting instrument. Create a tightly drafted \"Access Period\" and \"Access Procedures\" section that property management can follow without calling legal each time someone arrives at the front desk.\n\nDefine the permitted hours (typically normal business hours), the required notice period (24 to 48 business hours is standard), and the content of each notice: names and company of entering persons, purpose of the visit, equipment to be used, and confirmation that certificates of insurance are on file. Include a mechanism for the owner to require escorts, reschedule for operational reasons, or deny entry to individuals who fail to comply with safety or sign-in requirements.\n\nAddress tenant and occupant impacts explicitly. Require non-interference with tenants' quiet enjoyment, prohibit contacting tenants without owner's prior written consent, and require compliance with building rules and security protocols. In properties with existing tenants, the owner may have specific notice requirements under those leases before permitting third-party access to leased premises; the access agreement should acknowledge and respect those obligations. If there are unions, ask the user whether union labor must be used for certain tasks and incorporate or reference those rules if applicable.\n\nInclude safety and compliance language that is practical rather than boilerplate. If the buyer will perform any work that could implicate OSHA requirements, lockout/tagout procedures, roof fall protection, confined space entry, or hot work permits, address those specifically and require compliance, while flagging that operational safety protocols must be reviewed by the owner's facilities team.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how notice and coordination provisions should be structured:\n\n\"All entries shall be coordinated through Owner's designated representative, [NAME/TITLE], at [CONTACT INFORMATION]. Recipient shall provide at least [48] hours' prior written notice describing (i) the date and estimated time of entry, (ii) the identity of each individual entering the Property, (iii) the nature of the proposed activities and any equipment to be used, and (iv) confirmation that current certificates of insurance meeting the requirements hereof are on file with Owner. Owner may reasonably require that entries be escorted and may reschedule access to avoid interference with tenants, building operations, or safety requirements. Recipient shall not contact any tenant of the Property without Owner's prior written consent.\"\n\nA common drafting error is granting \"reasonable access\" without any notice protocol, which leads to disputes and tenant complaints. Another mistake is allowing after-hours access casually; if after-hours access is necessary for activities like fire alarm testing, require separate written approval and building engineer coordination.\n\nFrom a negotiation standpoint, buyers will push for unfettered 24/7 access. The owner must resist this to maintain security and tenant relations. However, to avoid a later argument that the seller unreasonably withheld access in order to extend the diligence period, include an objective reasonableness standard and an obligation to cooperate, while preserving the owner's operational control.\n\n### Step 3: Define Permitted Investigations Versus Invasive Activities, and Control Escalation\n\nThis is the most technically sensitive section of the agreement. You must draw a bright line between non-invasive diligence and invasive or destructive testing, because the risk profiles are categorically different.\n\nNon-invasive activities\u2014those permitted as of right\u2014include visual inspections, document review, Phase I Environmental Site Assessments conducted in accordance with ASTM E1527-21 [VERIFY], property condition assessments, surveys, architectural measurements, ADA observations, and review of readily available building systems. Invasive activities\u2014those requiring the owner's prior written consent\u2014include Phase II environmental sampling involving soil borings, groundwater testing, installation of monitoring wells, core sampling, cutting or penetration of roofs, slabs, pavements, or walls, disturbance of suspect asbestos-containing materials, and any activity that involves shutting down or interfering with building systems.\n\nThe default should be that no invasive testing is permitted without a separate, specific written approval based on a submitted \"Work Plan\" that includes the scope of work, sampling locations, schedule, contractor qualifications, proof of specialized insurance (including professional liability and, for environmental work, Contractor's Pollution Liability), and a restoration plan. The owner should have the right to approve sampling locations, be present during testing, and receive immediate notice of any release or hazardous condition discovered.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how this bifurcation should be structured:\n\n\"Recipient may perform the following non-invasive Investigations without further consent: visual inspections of improvements and site conditions; measurements and surveys; ADA observations; review of readily available building systems without disassembly; Phase I environmental site assessment activities that do not include physical sampling; and review of documents made available by Owner. Any Invasive Activities\u2014including without limitation soil borings, groundwater sampling, installation of monitoring wells, core sampling, cutting or penetration of roofs, slabs, pavements, or walls, or disturbance of suspect asbestos-containing or lead-based paint materials\u2014require Owner's prior written consent in Owner's reasonable discretion, based on a written Work Plan including the scope, schedule, contractor qualifications and licenses, evidence of applicable insurance, and a restoration plan.\"\n\nA common error is using a generic term like \"customary due diligence\" without enumerating what is permitted. This is too vague and invites disputes. Another common mistake is forgetting that ostensibly \"non-invasive\" consultants sometimes move ceiling tiles, open electrical panels, or shut down equipment\u2014activities that should be addressed and may require coordination even if they do not rise to the level of Phase II testing. Require pre-entry and post-entry condition photos and a log of sampling points for any invasive work.\n\nFor environmental work, be explicit about reporting and control of information. Discovery of contamination can trigger mandatory reporting obligations under federal law (CERCLA/RCRA) and state environmental statutes, and these obligations are highly jurisdiction- and fact-dependent [VERIFY]. Because the reporting duty can be statutory and nondelegable, the safest drafting requires prompt notice to owner and compliance with applicable law, while flagging to the user that environmental counsel should review the specific regulatory implications before invasive testing begins.\n\nFrom an adversarial perspective, buyers may later argue that the owner's refusal to consent to Phase II testing constituted a breach or unreasonable obstruction. Protect the owner with a \"reasonable discretion\" standard tied to objective criteria for approval (licensed contractor, adequate insurance, acceptable restoration plan, no material tenant disruption). If the buyer needs Phase II for financing, consider a negotiated pre-approval pathway tied to specific conditions.\n\nSome states regulate asbestos and lead-based paint disturbance and require licensed abatement contractors even for sampling activities [VERIFY]. Flag for attorney verification if the property is older or has known hazardous materials.\n\n### Step 4: Allocate Risk Through Insurance That Will Actually Respond, and Match It to the Indemnity\n\nInsurance language should be drafted with claims reality in mind. Certificates of insurance are not coverage documents; additional insured endorsements are what actually trigger the insurer's duty to defend and indemnify; and primary/noncontributory wording is often endorsement-driven, not automatically conferred by the certificate. Your job is to specify what must be procured and delivered, and to tie access permission to receipt of acceptable evidence of coverage.\n\nRequire commercial general liability (CGL) insurance on an occurrence form with appropriate limits. A common default is $1,000,000 per occurrence and $2,000,000 general aggregate, but limits should be adjusted based on property type and value (bracketed for negotiation). Require that Owner, property manager, and lender (if requested) are named as additional insureds for ongoing and completed operations on a primary and noncontributory basis. The relevant ISO additional insured endorsement forms are CG 20 10 (for ongoing operations) and CG 20 37 (for completed operations) [VERIFY]. Require waiver of subrogation where commercially feasible.\n\nFor consultants performing environmental or engineering work, require professional liability (errors and omissions) insurance. For environmental consultants specifically, require Contractor's Pollution Liability (CPL) coverage. These are critical because CGL policies typically exclude pollution liability, and an owner indemnified in contract but facing an uninsured consultant's error may have no practical recovery. For contractors doing invasive work, consider also requiring workers' compensation, employer's liability, automobile liability, and umbrella or excess coverage.\n\nInclude carrier quality requirements (e.g., AM Best A-/VII or equivalent) as a bracketed term. Require that policies not be canceled or materially modified without notice to the owner. Recognize that many carriers do not provide 30 days' prior notice to additional insureds as a matter of right under current endorsement forms, so treat it as a contractual obligation on the Recipient to provide prompt notice upon learning of cancellation, in addition to requesting the notice provision in the certificate.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how insurance requirements should be structured:\n\n\"As a condition to any entry, Recipient shall maintain, and shall cause each of Recipient's Representatives entering the Property to maintain, at Recipient's sole cost: (i) commercial general liability insurance on an ISO occurrence form with limits of not less than [$1,000,000] per occurrence and [$2,000,000] general aggregate; (ii) workers' compensation as required by law and employer's liability with limits of not less than [$500,000]; and (iii) if any Invasive Activities are approved, umbrella or excess liability insurance of not less than [$5,000,000] and Contractor's Pollution Liability insurance with limits of not less than [$1,000,000]. Owner, Owner's property manager, and [LENDER] shall be named as additional insureds under (i) and (iii) on a primary and noncontributory basis. Recipient shall deliver certificates of insurance and, upon Owner's request, copies of the additional insured and waiver of subrogation endorsements, prior to any entry. No entry shall occur until Owner has confirmed receipt of acceptable evidence of insurance.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include relying solely on certificates of insurance without requiring endorsements, omitting consultant-specific coverage requirements, and setting limits that the buyer cannot procure quickly (which delays diligence). A practical escalation structure\u2014baseline limits for non-invasive activities, higher limits for invasive work\u2014helps avoid this.\n\nFrom an adversarial perspective, after an incident, carriers routinely dispute tender based on missing endorsements, the scope of \"ongoing operations\" versus \"completed operations,\" or late notice. Draft to require the actual endorsements and impose prompt notice obligations.\n\nSome states restrict indemnity and insurance arrangements in construction-adjacent contexts through anti-indemnity statutes [VERIFY]. If the invasive work is extensive enough to resemble construction or alteration, these statutes may be implicated. Flag for attorney review.\n\n### Step 5: Draft Indemnity, Defense, and Survival to Reflect How Claims Actually Arise\n\nIndemnity is the owner's primary contractual risk transfer when insurance fails, is delayed, or has gaps. Draft indemnity that is broad enough to cover bodily injury and property damage, mechanics' liens or similar claims arising from the buyer's contractors, tenant claims arising from disruption, regulatory claims triggered by the buyer's activities, and the owner's costs of enforcement including reasonable attorneys' fees.\n\nInclude a defense obligation with counsel reasonably acceptable to the owner. Some jurisdictions interpret the contractual \"duty to defend\" narrowly or impose specific requirements for its enforceability [VERIFY]. Where enforceability is uncertain, draft both a defense obligation and a reimbursement obligation as a fallback: the Recipient has a duty to defend, and if that duty is not enforceable for any reason, the Recipient must reimburse the Owner's reasonable defense costs.\n\nThe most heavily negotiated point in these agreements is the treatment of pre-existing conditions. A sophisticated buyer will demand a carve-out for the mere discovery of conditions the buyer did not cause. This is commercially reasonable and should be addressed explicitly. The buyer should not be responsible for the cost of remediating a twenty-year-old fuel leak simply because its consultant found it. However, the buyer should remain liable for any damage caused by its activities and for any exacerbation of pre-existing conditions. A workable formulation: the Recipient indemnifies for damages caused by Recipient's actions, including any exacerbation of pre-existing conditions, but has no liability for the mere discovery of pre-existing conditions that Recipient did not cause or worsen\u2014while still requiring prompt notice to Owner of any such discovery and compliance with applicable law regarding reporting.\n\nIndemnity carve-outs for owner fault must be negotiated carefully. Owners typically agree to carve out losses caused by the owner's gross negligence or willful misconduct; some buyers insist on a carve-out for the owner's ordinary negligence as well. Because the enforceability of indemnification for a party's own negligence varies significantly by state and context, include bracketed options and instruct the user to select based on governing law and deal leverage.\n\nJurisdiction-specific enforcement rules are critical here. In Texas, the \"Express Negligence Doctrine\" requires that if the owner wants to be indemnified for its own negligence, that intent must be stated clearly and conspicuously (e.g., in bold or capitals), per Ethyl Corp. v. Daniel Const. Co., 725 S.W.2d 705 (Tex. 1987) [VERIFY]. In New York, General Obligations Law Section 5-322.1 may void indemnity provisions that purport to indemnify a party for its own negligence in certain real property contexts [VERIFY]. In California, similar restrictions apply under Civil Code provisions [VERIFY]. Failure to comply with these state-specific formatting and substantive rules can render the entire indemnity clause unenforceable. When the user provides the governing state, the LLM should conduct targeted web verification of that state's anti-indemnity regime and adjust the indemnity carve-outs accordingly, or flag the issue for attorney verification if web research is unavailable.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how the indemnity provision should be structured:\n\n\"Recipient shall indemnify, defend (with counsel reasonably acceptable to Owner), and hold harmless Owner, its affiliates, and their respective partners, members, managers, officers, directors, employees, agents, property manager, and lender (collectively, the 'Owner Indemnitees') from and against any and all claims, demands, causes of action, damages, losses, liabilities, liens, penalties, fines, costs, and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees and court costs) arising out of or relating to (i) any entry upon the Property by Recipient or any Recipient Representative, (ii) the performance of any Investigations or Invasive Activities, (iii) any breach of this Agreement by Recipient, or (iv) any injury to persons (including death) or damage to property caused by Recipient or any Recipient Representative; except that Recipient shall have no liability under this section for (a) the mere discovery of pre-existing conditions that Recipient did not cause or exacerbate, or (b) to the extent finally determined by a court of competent jurisdiction to have resulted from the [gross negligence or willful misconduct / sole negligence] of an Owner Indemnitee. [IN TEXAS AND OTHER EXPRESS NEGLIGENCE JURISDICTIONS: THE INDEMNIFICATION OBLIGATIONS SET FORTH IN THIS SECTION ARE INTENDED TO APPLY EVEN IF THE CLAIM ARISES IN WHOLE OR IN PART FROM THE NEGLIGENCE (BUT NOT THE SOLE NEGLIGENCE OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT) OF AN OWNER INDEMNITEE.]\"\n\nAdd survival language that is explicit. Avoid vague \"shall survive\" without stating duration. Consider \"The indemnity, defense, and hold harmless obligations of this Section shall survive the expiration or earlier termination of this Agreement for a period of [two (2)] years, or until all claims arising during the Access Period are finally resolved, whichever is later,\" subject to enforceability under applicable law [VERIFY].\n\nCommon mistakes include failing to include liens in the scope of indemnified losses, failing to cover the property manager and lender, not addressing attorneys' fees, and using inconsistent defined terms that create an argument that certain contractors are not \"Representatives.\"\n\n### Step 6: Restoration, Lien Control, and Incident Response\n\nRestoration provisions should be drafted like a remedy clause, not a vague promise. Require that the Recipient promptly repairs any damage to the property, improvements, landscaping, or personal property caused by Recipient or its Representatives. All repairs must restore the property to substantially the same or better condition as existed immediately prior to entry, using contractors acceptable to the owner where building systems are involved. Require documentation: pre-entry and post-entry photographs, as-built records of sampling points, and a completion sign-off.\n\nInclude a self-help remedy. If the Recipient fails to commence repairs within a specified period after notice (five business days for routine repairs, immediately for safety hazards), the owner may perform the work and invoice the Recipient for reasonable costs plus an administrative fee (typically 10 to 15 percent, bracketed for negotiation). Require the Recipient to remove all equipment, materials, and debris and to leave the property in a clean and orderly condition.\n\nAddress mechanics' liens and materialmen's liens with a strict covenant. If the buyer's consultant or contractor files a lien against the owner's fee interest because the buyer failed to pay, the consequences can be severe and time-consuming to resolve. Require the Recipient to keep the property free of all liens arising from its activities and to cause any such lien to be released, discharged, or bonded off within a short timeframe (e.g., ten days after notice). Lien procedures and bonding requirements are highly state-specific [VERIFY]; do not state specific statutory deadlines as requirements of law in the agreement, but impose contractual cure periods.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how the restoration and lien provisions should work together:\n\n\"Recipient shall promptly repair any damage to the Property caused by Recipient or any Recipient Representative and restore the affected areas to substantially the same condition existing immediately prior to entry. If Recipient fails to commence repairs within [5] business days after written notice (or immediately in the case of a safety hazard), Owner may perform such repairs and Recipient shall reimburse Owner's reasonable costs plus an administrative fee of [15]% within [10] days after invoice. Recipient shall not permit any mechanic's, materialman's, or similar lien to attach to the Property arising from Recipient's activities and shall cause any such lien to be released, discharged, or bonded off within [10] days after written notice from Owner.\"\n\nFrom an adversarial perspective, buyers may argue that damage pre-existed their entry. Address this by adding a pre-entry condition documentation requirement and a provision that the owner may observe and document the property's condition before and after each entry.\n\n### Step 7: Confidentiality, Report Ownership, and Controlled Disclosure\n\nDiligence produces sensitive information: rent rolls, delinquency data, security procedures, building plans, and environmental and engineering reports. The access agreement must specify confidentiality obligations even if a broader NDA exists, or it must cleanly incorporate the NDA by reference and avoid conflicting terms.\n\nDefine \"Confidential Information\" to include not only documents provided by the owner but also observations, measurements, photographs, drone footage, and work product derived from the Recipient's access. Permit disclosure to Recipient's Representatives with a need to know who are bound by written confidentiality obligations at least as protective as those in the agreement. Address compelled disclosure by requiring notice to the owner (to the extent legally permissible), cooperation in seeking protective orders, and disclosure limited to what is legally required.\n\nThe question of whether the owner should receive copies of the buyer's diligence reports is strategically significant and must be addressed thoughtfully. Owners sometimes require copies of third-party reports, especially environmental reports, as a condition of granting access. However, if a buyer's consultant finds a Recognized Environmental Condition (\"REC\"), providing that report to the owner may give the owner \"actual knowledge\" of the condition, which in some jurisdictions can trigger a legal obligation to disclose to future buyers or regulatory bodies under state transfer act laws (e.g., New Jersey's Industrial Site Recovery Act, Connecticut's Transfer Act) [VERIFY]. A practical approach is to require delivery of non-privileged factual data resulting from invasive activities (such as sampling logs and analytical results) while allowing the parties to negotiate whether full interpretive reports must be shared. If the owner elects not to receive reports, include an express statement that the owner is declining receipt to avoid triggering any \"actual knowledge\" consequences.\n\nThe following illustrative language demonstrates how confidentiality provisions should be structured:\n\n\"Recipient shall keep all Confidential Information strictly confidential and shall use it solely for evaluating the contemplated transaction. Recipient may disclose Confidential Information only to its Representatives who have a need to know and who are bound by written confidentiality obligations no less protective than those herein. If Recipient is required by law or legal process to disclose any Confidential Information, Recipient shall (to the extent legally permitted) provide Owner prompt written notice and cooperate with Owner in seeking confidential treatment or a protective order. Upon termination of this Agreement without closing, Recipient shall promptly return or destroy all Confidential Information, except that Recipient may retain one archival copy for legal compliance purposes subject to continued confidentiality obligations.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include forgetting that photographs, drone footage, and floorplans are confidential and can create security risks, and creating conflicting confidentiality terms between the NDA and the access agreement. If an NDA exists, include an explicit statement of which document controls with respect to confidentiality, or harmonize the terms.\n\nOwners may want express injunctive relief language for confidentiality and unauthorized entry breaches, on the basis that monetary damages alone would be inadequate. This is generally enforceable in commercial agreements, though the enforceability of specific injunctive relief clauses varies by state [VERIFY]. Frame it as an agreed remedy: \"The parties agree that a breach of this Section would cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages would be inadequate, and Owner shall be entitled to seek injunctive relief in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity.\"\n\n### Step 8: Owner Disclaimers, Termination, Dispute Mechanics, and Integration\n\nAn access agreement is not a disclosure instrument. Include a clear \"as-is\" and \"no representations\" clause confirming that the buyer is entering the property and conducting inspections at its own risk, that the owner makes no representations or warranties regarding the condition of the property or the accuracy or completeness of any information provided, and that the buyer is responsible for its own independent investigation and evaluation. This helps prevent later fraud-by-omission theories based solely on access discussions, though it will not bar claims based on intentional fraud or misrepresentation [VERIFY].\n\nDefine termination mechanics clearly. The agreement commences on the effective date and continues until the earliest of: a specified termination date, closing of the purchase transaction, termination of the underlying PSA, or written termination by either party upon material breach and failure to cure within a specified period. Clarify which provisions survive termination: indemnification, confidentiality, restoration, lien discharge, and insurance obligations for completed operations must all expressly survive.\n\nDispute provisions should be commercially realistic. Specify governing law and venue. Include notice provisions with addresses for each party and the property manager. Consider whether to include attorneys' fees provisions. Include a requirement that any onsite emergencies be reported immediately to the owner and local authorities.\n\nIf a PSA or NDA exists, include a priority clause addressing potential conflicts:\n\n\"If the parties have entered into a Purchase and Sale Agreement for the Property, the access provisions of such agreement shall control to the extent of any express conflict; provided that the insurance, indemnity, restoration, and confidentiality obligations set forth herein shall remain in full force unless such Purchase and Sale Agreement expressly supersedes them by specific reference to this Agreement.\"\n\nInclude standard integration and amendment clauses. State that the agreement constitutes the entire agreement regarding property access and supersedes all prior understandings on the subject. Provide that no amendment is effective unless in writing signed by both parties. Add a severability clause, an assignment restriction (typically prohibiting assignment without the owner's consent), and a provision clarifying that the agreement does not confer third-party beneficiary rights except as expressly stated.\n\nConclude with properly formatted signature blocks for both parties. If either party is an entity, ensure the signature block reflects proper corporate or organizational authority with signature line, printed name, title, and date. Consider including acknowledgment or notarization language if the agreement will be recorded or if state law requires it for certain provisions to be enforceable [VERIFY].\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\nThis skill produces a client-facing contract and implicates core professional responsibility duties. Competence under Model Rule 1.1 requires the drafter to understand contract enforceability, premises liability risk allocation, insurance mechanics, and environmental diligence implications. An attorney who does not understand the technical difference between a Phase I and Phase II Environmental Site Assessment cannot competently draft the Permitted Activities section.\n\nCommunication obligations under Model Rule 1.4 require explaining to the client what the agreement does not solve: it does not eliminate statutory environmental reporting duties, it does not guarantee that insurance will respond to every claim, and it does not create disclosure obligations on the owner beyond those in the PSA or applicable law.\n\nIf the LLM is assisting counsel for one party, it must not imply it represents the other party and should avoid language that could create confusion about who is the client, consistent with Model Rules 4.3 and 1.13. Candor to third parties under Model Rule 4.1 is relevant when the access agreement is used to obtain certificates of insurance, endorsements, or permits; do not draft language that encourages misleading certificates or misstatements to insurers.\n\nConflicts must be screened at the matter level. If the user indicates the firm represents both parties or related parties (e.g., owner and property manager), the LLM should flag the need for conflict checks and appropriate waivers under Model Rules 1.7, 1.8, and 1.9.\n\nThe Work Product Doctrine may not protect a third-party consultant's report unless that consultant was specifically retained by legal counsel to provide legal advice in anticipation of litigation. If the buyer wants to preserve privilege over diligence reports, the engagement structure must be reviewed by litigation counsel.\n\nMalpractice risk hotspots include: using indemnity language unenforceable under the governing state's anti-indemnity statute; failing to require endorsement evidence for additional insured status; failing to control invasive testing and restoration; drafting confidentiality that conflicts with an existing NDA or PSA; and including hallucinated legal citations. The LLM must not invent case law, statutes, or regulatory requirements. Any reference to specific state statutes, lien deadlines, anti-indemnity rules, or environmental reporting obligations must be verified via web research at the time of use or flagged prominently with [VERIFY] for attorney confirmation.\n\nAll output from this skill requires review by an attorney licensed in the jurisdiction where the property is located. This document is a draft and does not constitute legal advice.\n\n## 6. Quality Control and Review\n\nA competent review begins with internal consistency and operational realism. Confirm that defined terms\u2014\"Property,\" \"Access Period,\" \"Investigations,\" \"Invasive Activities,\" \"Recipient's Representatives,\" \"Owner Indemnitees,\" \"Confidential Information\"\u2014are used consistently throughout. Check that the access protocol is administrable: notice method, who receives it, whether weekends and holidays affect deadlines, and whether the property manager has been included in the notice chain.\n\nEnsure the insurance section requires not just certificates but endorsements upon request, and that the limits align with the property's risk profile and any lender requirements. Verify that the insurance requirements escalate appropriately for invasive activities.\n\nTest the indemnity for litigation posture. Read it as if you are a claims adjuster tendering a defense: does it clearly cover defense costs, property manager, lender, tenant claims, and contractor-caused losses? Does it include liens? Does the \"discovery\" carve-out work cleanly, or does it create ambiguity about what \"caused by\" means? Read the restoration clause as if you are the property manager after a botched core sample: can you self-help and recover costs quickly, including the administrative fee?\n\nRead confidentiality as if you are seeking an injunction: is \"Confidential Information\" defined broadly enough, is injunctive relief framed as an agreed remedy, and does the provision address photographs, drone footage, and security information?\n\nCheck for factual support and accuracy. The agreement should not state that a legal requirement exists unless verified. If the draft includes statements about statutory reporting, lien law procedures, or state-specific indemnity limits, the LLM must either provide a verified source or mark the statement [VERIFY] for attorney confirmation.\n\nEnsure bracketed business terms are clearly marked and limited to a manageable number: insurance limits, notice period, Access Period end date, administrative fee percentage, cure periods, and governing law and venue. Avoid unnecessary one-sidedness that will delay signature unless the user has specified that they represent the owner and desire seller-protective language.\n\nThe final agreement should typically be four to seven pages in length depending on complexity, formatted for standard letter-size paper with appropriate margins for binding and execution, with section numbering and professional formatting suitable for immediate use upon insertion of deal-specific terms.\n\n## 7. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nThis skill is written for general US practice because access agreements are primarily contract-driven, but several issues vary materially by state and must be adapted when the governing law and property location are known.\n\nIndemnity enforceability changes significantly based on state anti-indemnity statutes, especially where diligence work begins to resemble construction or alteration. Key jurisdictions include New York (General Obligations Law Section 5-322.1, which may void certain indemnity provisions in real property contexts) [VERIFY], Texas (the Express Negligence Doctrine requiring conspicuous language per Ethyl Corp. v. Daniel Const. Co.) [VERIFY], California (Civil Code restrictions on indemnity for sole negligence) [VERIFY], and Florida (similar statutory limitations) [VERIFY]. When the user provides the governing state, the LLM should conduct targeted web verification of that state's anti-indemnity regime and adjust the carve-outs accordingly.\n\nMechanics' lien concepts and lien discharge or bonding procedures are highly state-specific. The agreement can impose contractual lien cure timelines, but the LLM must not represent statutory deadlines without verification. If the property is in a state with unusual lien rules, attorney review is essential.\n\nEnvironmental sampling and reporting obligations are highly jurisdiction- and fact-dependent. In states like New Jersey (Industrial Site Recovery Act) and Connecticut (Transfer Act), the mere act of conducting certain types of environmental due diligence may trigger state-monitored investigation or cleanup requirements if certain thresholds are met [VERIFY]. Where the contemplated diligence includes Phase II work, the LLM should recommend environmental counsel review and should avoid definitive statements about mandatory reporting triggers absent verified authority.\n\nCalifornia practitioners should consider whether a waiver of Civil Code Section 1542 is appropriate if the indemnity includes a release of unknown claims [VERIFY]. New York practitioners should be mindful of General Obligations Law Section 5-321, which may limit an owner's ability to exempt itself from liability for its own negligence in licenses related to real property [VERIFY].\n\nEnforceability of exculpatory language, liability waivers, and agreed injunctive relief varies by state. The skill therefore emphasizes insurance, indemnity, and restoration\u2014generally enforceable commercial allocations\u2014and treats any broader liability waivers as optional, bracketed, and subject to attorney verification under governing law.",
